---
import CapRateNoiCalculator from "@/components/calculators/CapRateNoiCalculator";
import ToolShell from "@/components/dscr/ToolShell.astro";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What is a cap rate calculator used for in multifamily?",
    a: "A cap rate calculator converts stabilized net operating income (NOI) and property value into an implied cap rate—or backs into value from NOI and a market cap rate. Lenders and sponsors use it to sanity-check pricing on 5+ unit apartment acquisitions and refinances.",
  },
  {
    q: "How do you calculate cap rate?",
    a: "Cap Rate = NOI ÷ Property Value. For example, $900,000 NOI on a $15,000,000 asset implies a 6.0% cap rate. Reverse the formula to estimate value: Value = NOI ÷ Cap Rate.",
  },
  {
    q: "What NOI should I use for a cap rate calculation?",
    a: "Use lender-normalized NOI: trailing T12 or T3 annualized, with nonrecurring items removed and realistic vacancy, concessions, and expense assumptions. Sponsors often model both in-place and stabilized NOI.",
  },
  {
    q: "Is cap rate the same as cash-on-cash return?",
    a: "No. Cap rate is an unlevered yield on property value. Cash-on-cash measures levered return on equity after debt service. Both matter, but lenders size debt from NOI, DSCR, and debt yield—not cap rate alone.",
  },
  {
    q: "What cap rate range is typical for stabilized multifamily?",
    a: "Ranges vary widely by market, vintage, and asset quality. Many stabilized 5+ unit assets underwrite between roughly 4.5% and 7.5%, but submarket comps and lender adjustments should drive your assumption—not a national average.",
  },
  {
    q: "Can I use this calculator for value-add deals?",
    a: "Yes. Run in-place NOI for today's pricing context and stabilized NOI for exit or refinance scenarios. Bridge lenders often underwrite both views when sizing proceeds and extension risk.",
  },
];
---

<ToolShell
  title="Cap Rate Calculator for Multifamily | Multi-Family USA"
  description="Free cap rate calculator for 5+ unit multifamily. Model NOI, operating expenses, and implied cap rate with a worked apartment building example."
  h1="Cap Rate Calculator for Multifamily"
  toolSlug="cap-rate-noi-calculator"
  tagline="Model stabilized income, operating expenses, and implied market cap rates for commercial apartment buildings."
  keywords={["cap rate calculator", "noi calculator", "multifamily cap rate", "apartment valuation", "net operating income"]}
  relatedGuides={["multifamily-noi-normalization", "multifamily-underwriting-basics", "five-plus-unit-commercial-financing-basics"]}
  relatedComparisons={["agency-vs-bridge", "acquisition-vs-refinance"]}
  relatedPropertyTypes={["garden-style-multifamily", "value-add-c-class-multifamily"]}
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <Fragment slot="calculator">
    <CapRateNoiCalculator client:load />
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="content">
    <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none dark:prose-invert">
      <h2>How to calculate cap rate for multifamily</h2>
      <p>
        Cap rate expresses how much annual NOI a property produces relative to its price. For commercial multifamily (5+ units), the core formula is:
      </p>
      <p><strong>Cap Rate = NOI ÷ Property Value</strong></p>
      <p>
        To solve for value instead: <strong>Property Value = NOI ÷ Cap Rate</strong>. Always use normalized NOI—gross income minus vacancy, concessions, and operating expenses—before applying the formula.
      </p>

      <h2>Worked example: 48-unit garden-style apartment</h2>
      <p>
        A sponsor underwrites a 48-unit garden-style property in a Sun Belt market. Effective gross income is $1,152,000 after vacancy and concessions. Operating expenses total $432,000, producing <strong>NOI of $720,000</strong>. The seller asks $12,000,000.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Implied cap rate: $720,000 ÷ $12,000,000 = <strong>6.0%</strong></li>
        <li>If market comps support a 5.75% cap, implied value = $720,000 ÷ 0.0575 ≈ <strong>$12.5M</strong></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Lenders may haircut revenue or stress expenses, which lowers NOI and raises the effective cap rate on their value opinion. Pair this output with the <a href="/tools/debt-yield-calculator">debt yield calculator</a> and <a href="/learn/multifamily-noi-normalization">NOI normalization guide</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Fragment>
</ToolShell>
